k","Whitfield, Northumberland, England":"Whitfield, Northumberland, England"},"en":{"about 1369–":"about 1369–Deceased","1365–1409":"1365–1409","1365–Female":"1365–Deceased","1367–1397":"1367–1397","1369–Female":"1369–Deceased","–1367":"–1367","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","1364–1438":"1364–1438","1388–1491":"1388–1491","1410–1492":"1410–1492","1346–1409":"1346–1409","1347–Female":"1347–Deceased","1382":"1382","1492":"1492","1360":"1360","1491":"1491","1347":"1347","1369":"1369","1346":"1346","Abt 1410":"about 1410","1367":"1367","1455":"1455","1388":"1388","1410":"1410","about 1369":"about 1369","1365":"1365","1386":"1386","1364":"1364","1397":"1397","1409":"1409","1438":"1438","England":"England, United Kingdom","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Whitfield, Northumberland, England":"Whitfield, Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mitford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Mitford (Northumb)."],"variants":[{"name":"Medforth","meanings":["English:  see  Mitford  ."]},{"name":"Midforth","meanings":["English:  see  Mitford  ."]},{"name":"Metford","meanings":["English:  see  Mitford  ."]},{"name":"Medford","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Mitford</b>, a habitational name from Mitford (Northumberland). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>midd</i> ‘middle’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"Midford","meanings":["English:  see  Mitford  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":13,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":86,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Mitford was born about 1369, in Northumberland, England, her father, John de Mitford, was 24 and her mother, Emma G. de Fawden, was 23. She married John Whitfield in 1386, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons."},"et":{"about 1369–":"umbes 1369–Surnud","1365–1409":"1365–1409","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1367–1397":"1367–1397","1369–Female":"1369–Surnud","–1367":"–1367","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1364–1438":"1364–1438","1388–1491":"1388–1491","1410–1492":"1410–1492","1346–1409":"1346–1409","1347–Female":"1347–Surnud","1